reviewText: Good lecture.

I really liked the lecture and thought it brought out more than the fallen angels but thought it really shows the Lordship of Jesus Christ in relation to the story being told which is the purpose and intent of the Bible. It was very good and Brian Godawa really goes through scripture to prove his point.

A conference/discussion of why Brian Godawa choose to write about the Nephilim. I really enjoyed his point of view and the numerous bible references through out his discussion, which really is important for having credibility. Even though it is an interpretation, in some sense, there is many references and critical thinking that show truth to the controversy. I have not read the books but this video definitely makes me want to open up the series. Obviously I would read them for entertainment value and not factual although he uses many bible passages to write his story.
If I could as for my 1.99 back I would.

Dr. Godawa connects the dots with his theory of the spirit world and the material world operating in parallel.  By dots I mean Biblical verses that seem odd and out of place on their own, like 1 Peter 3:19-20, but which make perfect sense with just a bit of connective tissue which Godawa supplies.  I especially like the fact that he honors the Word and brings everything back to the importance and pre-eminence of Jesus as the Son of God and Savior of the world. We're fortunate to have such a creative and expert mind working all this out for us!
returned dvd, boring lecture.. better off using Google..

Why would anyone give this presentation less than 5 stars? If it is not what you expected, that is no reflection on the very well done presentation itself. For those of us who have read our Bibles, we know that there are things that are mysterious and their unveiling requires just what this author has done. He follows a line and makes connections that brings clarity to certain mysteries-- especially regarding the important role of the Nephilim and their opposition to God and the woman and the seed of the woman. The author is very articulate and honest for his position, and even if I never come to a place of agreement with him on this subject, I know that he has caused me to think about the word of God to a greater degree.
